3. The Causative - Form and use the causative

The Causative

In this lesson, we'll follow Raul who is travelling around TÃ¼rkiye by car. ğŸš˜ ğŸ—ºï¸
It's a great plan...until it isn't! Raul finds himself using the causative 
("Can I have my teeth checked?") to ask other people to do something for him.

Who is Raul calling?
breakdown services

Why was Raul relieved?
He could communicate easily.
Raul's car wasn't serviced recently and can't be repaired roadside.

"Raul had his car serviced a year ago." What does this sentence mean?
A mechanic checked that everything is fine with the car.

 the action happened in the past.
 what happened to the car.
 Raul had his car serviced a year ago
 had 
serviced

Raul had his car serviced a year ago.
The important information is what happened not who did it.

Have something done
"Have something done" is used when someone does something for us because 
we instruct them to, especially when we pay for a service. ğŸ’°

The hairdresser cut my hair. â†’ "I had my hair cut."

"Have" is the verb that changes its form.
"I'm having my door painted next week." 

The verb that describes the action is always in the past participle ("-ed" or irregular form).
"I have my teeth checked once a year."

The object (e.g. my hair) comes between "have" and the "-ed" form. 
"I had my hair cut."

She had her carpet cleaned yesterday.
I have had my nails done this morning.
I had my phone fixed at a low cost.

Get something done
You can use "get" instead of "have" in these sentences and the meaning is the same. 

"I had my car serviced."
"I got my car serviced."

"He's having his hair cut."
"He's getting his hair cut."

Linda got her living room redecorated.
She asked somebody, probably an interior designer, to do it for her.

What is Raul worried about?
Raul is worried that his...insurance won't pay for the repairs.

He had a spark plug correctly installed.
Getting his brakes repaired cost Raul a lot of money.
He has got two tyres replaced.
Raul has had the oil changed.

