4. More about the causative - Talk about someone doing something for you

Here's a tip!
In the previous lesson, we looked at the causative form "have/get something done".
 
"I got my hair cut."
The action, not the person who does the action, is important

You feel you can't see very well and want to get medical advice. What do you say?
I need to get my eyes tested.

Here's a tip!
In this lesson, we'll learn two new causative structures used to mention 
who does the action â€“ "have somebody do something" and "get somebody to do something"

But first, we're going to listen to a conversation between two friends Clara and Joel. 
Here is some vocabulary that will help you understand them a little better.
Vocabulary
a bad hair day (n) â€“  a day when you don't feel attractive and everything goes wrong 
yikes (exclamation) â€“ an informal way to show that you're surprised, worried or shocked
freaking (adj) â€“ an informal way to intensify what is being said 

Clara: Jesus, man! What happened to you? Having a bad hair day?
Joel: Ha, ha, ha very funny. ... I've cut my own hair. I watched this 
tutorial on YouTube and it looked very easy, but it wasn't. Here's the result.
Clara: First, yikes - you'll need to wear a hat for a long time and second 
your mom is a freaking hairdresser, why didn't you have your mom cut your hair? 

Why can't Clara stop laughing?
Joel's hair looks ridiculous.

"Why didn't you have your mom cut your hair?"
Carla thinks that Joel should have asked his mom to cut his hair.

"Have somebody do something"
If you want to mention who does an action for you because you instruct them 
or ask them to, use "have somebody do something". 

"Have" is the verb that changes its form.
"I had the waiter bring the menu."

The verb describing the action is in its basic form.
"She had the children clean their room."

I cut my hair. - I did the action.
I had my hair cut. - I paid somebody to do the action.
I had my mom cut my hair. - My mom did the action.

I had my hair cut. - focus on the action
I had my mom cut my hair. - focus on the person who does the action

I had the taxi driver drive faster.
I'll have my colleague read the report.

"Get somebody to do something"
You can use "get somebody to do something" instead of "have somebody do something".

ğŸ›ï¸ Watch out for the "to" that goes with "get somebody to do something". ğŸ›ï¸
I had my mum cut my hair.
I got my mum to cut my hair. 
I got my friend to look after my children.

You're calling your dentist because your teeth hurt. What do you say?
I'd like to get the dentist to check my teeth.

You've bought groceries online and are now waiting for the delivery. 
What do you say?
I'm having the supermarket deliver the shopping.

a similar meaning to I had the mechanic fix the brakes.
I got the mechanic to fix the brakes.

You want your assistant to help you send some emails. What do you say?
I'll have my assistant send|get my assistant to send these emails.

Your windows need cleaning and you want your boyfriend to do it. 
What do you say?

I'm going to get my boyfriend to clean|have my boyfriend clean the windows.
have my boyfriend clean

Final recap
Now you know how to use the causative to talk about things other people do for you! ğŸ‘

Here are all the forms:

have/get something done
the focus is on the action
"I had my nails done."

have somebody do something
get somebody to do something 
the focus is on the person
"I got my sister to do my nails."

