5. Unreal/mixed conditionals - Form and use mixed conditionals

If I were you, I would tell her the truth.
I'm talking about an unreal present or hypothetical situation and a consequence.
The 2nd conditional imagines a hypothetical situation (if I were you) 
and a present consequence.

If I had more time, I would go to the gym.

If I were Richard, I would have applied for that job ages ago.
This conditional mixes a hypothetical situation (if I were Richard) 
and a past consequence (I would have applied).

A mixed (hypothetical) conditional
************************************
We use "if" and the past simple ("were") to introduce 
a hypothetical situation, but you can either use:

1. "would/could/might" and the infinitive ("be") to refer to a present consequence
or
2. "would/could/might" and the present perfect ("have been") to refer to 
a past consequence (which is one type of mixed conditional).

a present consequence (2nd conditional)
"If he weren't already married, I would be his wife now."

a past consequence (mixed conditional)
"If he weren't already married, I would have married him."

"If he weren't already married..."
I would have married him myself. - a different past consequence
I would be his wife now. - a different present consequence

If he weren't your friend, I would have fired him ages ago.
Kamo wouldn't have got the modelling gig if he weren't so handsome.
If he weren't already married, I would have married him.

You're a star! ğŸŒŸ
You've just learned one way to create a mixed conditional sentence! ğŸ˜ƒ
Next we'll look at how to mix up the 3rd (past) conditional! ğŸ¥„

Did you know? ğŸ’¡
You can change the order of the two parts of the sentence and 
write the consequence before the situation. Look at these examples. ğŸ‘‡

I would have married him myself, if he weren't already married.
I'd (I would) be rich if I had a dollar for every time I heard that.

I would've recovered faster if I had taken the pills.
The past conditional imagines a past situation (if I had taken pills) 
and a past consequence (I would have recovered).

We would have finished the report yesterday if we had started writing last week.

If I had saved around 10% of my income, I could buy a house now.
I'm talking about a past situation and a present consequence.
This is a mixed conditional with a past situation (if I had saved 10%) and 
a present consequence (I could buy a house).

Another mixed conditional!
The rules are generally similar to the first type of mixed conditional, 
but do note the differences in verb tenses!

We use "if" and the past perfect ("had been") to introduce a past situation, 
but you can either use:

1. "would/could/might" and the present perfect ("have been") to refer to a past consequence
or
2. "would/could/might" and the infinitive ("be") to refer to a 
present consequence (which is another type of mixed conditional).

a past consequence (3rd conditional)
If we had left earlier, we would have been on time.

a present consequence (mixed conditional)
If we had left earlier, we would be at the party now.

"If we had left the house earlier..."
...we would have been on time. - a different past consequence
...we would be at the party now. - a different present consequence

If Vince had listened to the doctor, he wouldn't need surgery.
The singer would be in jail if the press had reported his tax evasion.

"I would have passed the maths test if the exam board rules allowed the use of calculators."
The exam board usually doesn't allow calculators so I failed the test.

If I hadn't learned Spanish, I wouldn't be qualified for the job in Madrid."

"I wouldn't have burned the eggs..."if I knew how to cook.
"If I weren't so busy these days..."I would have travelled abroad.

We asked members of the public... ğŸ¤
You're going to listen to a vox pop (or "voice of the people", 
a quick interview with random people on the street) where each person answers 
the question below.

Think about (or write down) your answer to this question. 
We'd love to hear from you in the next Busuu Community post! ğŸ¥°

Think of one skill you have.
What wouldn't you have achieved without it?

Think of one skill you have. What wouldn't you have achieved without it?
****************************************
Person 1: Definitely organisation. We just bought a new house and 
I'd never have been able to finish unpacking over the weekend 
if I weren't so organised.     

Person 2: Thank goodness I learned French at uni. 
That's the only reason why I applied for the job in Paris.

Person 3: Skills? [laughs] I'll tell you the opposite. 
If I weren't so clumsy, I wouldn't have broken my grandma's favourite vase 
when playing football in the house.

Person 4: I don't like to give up. If I weren't so stubborn, 
I wouldn't have passed my driving test after failing 5 times.

Person 5: You know, My fear of injections really stopped me from studying medicine, 
so I never ended up being a doctor.

"I'd never have been able to finish unpacking over the weekend if I weren't so organised."
Person 1 finished unpacking because she's organised.

If I didn't speak French, my job application would have been rejected.
If I weren't so clumsy, I wouldn't have broken my grandma's favourite vase.
If I weren't so stubborn, I wouldn't have passed my driving test after failing 5 times.
I probably would've become a doctor if I weren't so afraid of needles!

